<subsection xml:id="subsection-brief-reminder-vectors">
    <title>Brief reminder: vectors</title>

    <introduction>
        <p>
            In physics, many real-world quantities—such as force, velocity, or displacement—cannot be fully described by a single number. For example, if you apply a force to push a box, the outcome depends not only on how hard you push (the magnitude) but also on the direction in which you are pushing. 
             
            To capture both magnitude and direction simultaneously, we use mathematical objects called vectors. This concept extends naturally beyond physical space into abstract mathematics, allowing us to handle multi-dimensional spaces and systems.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    
    <definition xml:id="def-vector">
        <title>Vector</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A <term>vector</term> of size <m>n</m> is defined as an ordered tuple of <m>n</m> real numbers. The set containing all vectors of size <m>n</m> is represented by <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>. A vector <m>\mathbf{v} \in \mathbb{R}^n</m> is commonly denoted by its components as <m>\mathbf{v} = (v_1, \dots, v_n)</m> or as a column:
                <me>\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} v_1 \\ \vdots \\ v_n \end{pmatrix}</me>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
        Let us look at a concrete numerical representation of a vector in three-dimensional space.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="ex-vector">
        <title>A Vector in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m></title>
        <p>
            An example of a vector in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> is <m>\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix}</m>.
        </p>
    </example>

    <p>
        Geometrically, vectors can be interpreted as arrows in Euclidean space that possess a direction and a length without a clearly defined starting point, or they can be understood as position vectors that specifically start in the origin.
    </p>

    <p>
        To make vectors useful, we need mathematical rules for how to combine them. The two most fundamental operations are adding two vectors together and scaling a vector by a real number.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-vector-operations">
        <title>Vector Operations</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Vectors can be added together and scaled using real numbers (scalars).
            </p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Addition</title>
                    <p>The sum of two vectors <m>\mathbf{v}</m> and <m>\mathbf{w}</m> is determined by component-wise addition, yielding 
                    <me>\mathbf{v}+\mathbf{w} = \begin{pmatrix} v_1+w_1 \\ \vdots \\ v_n+w_n \end{pmatrix}</me>.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Scalar Multiplication</title>
                    <p>The multiplication of a scalar <m>\lambda \in \mathbb{R}</m> with a vector <m>\mathbf{v}</m> is given by multiplying each individual component by the scalar, resulting in 
                    <me>\lambda \mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} \lambda v_1 \\ \vdots \\ \lambda v_n \end{pmatrix}</me>.</p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </statement>
    </definition>

    <example xml:id="ex-vector-operations">
        <title>Calculating Sums and Scalar Multiples</title>
        <p>
            Let <m>\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}</m> and <m>\mathbf{w} = \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -2 \end{pmatrix}</m> be vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Their sum is:
            <me>\mathbf{v} + \mathbf{w} = \begin{pmatrix} 1+4 \\ 3+(-2) \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 5 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}</me>.
        </p>
        <p>
            If we scale the vector <m>\mathbf{v}</m> by a scalar <m>\lambda = 3</m>, we get:
            <me>3\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} 3 \cdot 1 \\ 3 \cdot 3 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 9 \end{pmatrix}</me>.
        </p>
    </example>

    <figure xml:id="fig-geogebra-vector-addition">
        <title>Interactive: Vector Addition</title>
        <interactive geogebra="vgqcxgyn" aspect="4:3" width="80%">
            <instructions>
                <p>Drag the heads of vectors <m>\mathbf{v}</m> and <m>\mathbf{w}</m> to see how their sum <m>\mathbf{v}+\mathbf{w}</m> changes geometrically via the parallelogram rule.</p>
            </instructions>
        </interactive>
    </figure>

    <figure xml:id="fig-geogebra-scalar-multiplication">
        <title>Interactive: Scalar Multiplication</title>
        <interactive geogebra="material_id_2" aspect="4:3" width="80%">
            <instructions>
                <p>Use the slider for <m>\lambda</m> to see how the scalar stretches, shrinks, or reverses the direction of the vector <m>\mathbf{v}</m>.</p>
            </instructions>
        </interactive>
    </figure>

    <p>
        Having established these basic arithmetic operations, a special and necessary vector arises naturally when we scale any vector by zero, or when we subtract a vector from itself.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-null-vector">
        <title>Null Vector</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The <term>null vector</term> (or zero vector) in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> is the vector consisting entirely of zeros. It is denoted by <m>\mathbf{0}</m> and is written as 
                <me>\mathbf{0} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ \vdots \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}</me>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
        Just like standard numbers, vector operations satisfy several foundational algebraic properties.
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-vector-arithmetic">
        <title>Laws of Vector Arithmetic</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Several important laws of vector arithmetic govern operations for vectors <m>\mathbf{u}, \mathbf{v}, \mathbf{w} \in \mathbb{R}^n</m> and scalars <m>\lambda, \mu \in \mathbb{R}</m>:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li><p><term>Associativity of Addition:</term> <m>\mathbf{u}+(\mathbf{v}+\mathbf{w})=(\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{v})+\mathbf{w}</m></p></li>
                <li><p><term>Commutativity of Addition:</term> <m>\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{v}+\mathbf{u}</m></p></li>
                <li><p><term>Neutral Element:</term> The null vector serves as the neutral element, leading to <m>\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{0}=\mathbf{0}+\mathbf{u}=\mathbf{u}</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p><term>Inverse Element:</term> Adding a vector to its negative yields the null vector: <m>\mathbf{u}+(-\mathbf{u})=(-\mathbf{u})+\mathbf{u}=\mathbf{0}</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p><term>Left Distributivity:</term> <m>\lambda \cdot (\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{v}) = (\lambda \cdot \mathbf{u}) + (\lambda \cdot \mathbf{v})</m></p></li>
                <li><p><term>Right Distributivity:</term> <m>(\lambda+\mu) \cdot \mathbf{u} = (\lambda \cdot \mathbf{u}) + (\mu \cdot \mathbf{u})</m></p></li>
                <li><p><term>Associativity of Scalar Multiplication:</term> <m>(\lambda \cdot \mu) \cdot \mathbf{u} = \lambda \cdot (\mu \cdot \mathbf{u})</m></p></li>
                <li><p><term>Multiplication by One:</term> <m>1 \cdot \mathbf{u} = \mathbf{u}</m></p></li>
            </ul>
        </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>
        When working with multiple vectors, it is crucial to determine if they represent genuinely distinct geometric directions. For instance, if one vector is merely a scaled version of another, or if it can be formed by adding other vectors together, it does not provide a "new" dimension or direction in space. This conceptualizes the idea of vectors being independent of one another.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-geogebra-linear-independence">
        <title>Interactive: Visualizing Linear Independence</title>
        <interactive geogebra="material_id_3" aspect="4:3" width="80%"> 
            <instructions>
                <p>Move the vectors to observe what happens when they become collinear or coplanar (linearly dependent) versus when they point in entirely distinct geometric directions (linearly independent).</p>
            </instructions>
        </interactive>
    </figure>

    <definition xml:id="def-linear-independence-basis">
        <title>Linear Independence and Basis</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Vectors <m>\mathbf{v}_1, \dots, \mathbf{v}_r \in \mathbb{R}^n</m> are considered <term>linearly independent</term> if the equation 
                <me>x_1 \mathbf{v}_1 + \dots + x_r \mathbf{v}_r = \mathbf{0}</me> 
                has only the trivial solution <m>x_1 = \dots = x_r = 0</m>. 
            </p>
            <p>
                A tuple of <m>n</m> linearly independent vectors <m>(\mathbf{v}_1, \dots, \mathbf{v}_n)</m> in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> is referred to as a <term>basis</term> of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
        The most intuitive example of a basis relies on the standard coordinate axes we use for graphing.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="ex-basis">
        <title>Standard Basis in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m></title>
        <p>
            The vectors <m>\mathbf{e}_1 = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}</m> and <m>\mathbf{e}_2 = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}</m> are linearly independent. The equation <m>x_1 \mathbf{e}_1 + x_2 \mathbf{e}_2 = \mathbf{0}</m> translates to <m>\begin{pmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}</m>, which forces <m>x_1 = 0</m> and <m>x_2 = 0</m>. Therefore, the tuple <m>(\mathbf{e}_1, \mathbf{e}_2)</m> forms a basis for <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>.
        </p>
    </example>

    <p>
        Beyond finding independent directions, we often need to measure the geometric properties of vectors, such as their exact length or the angle between them. We define these metric properties through a specific multiplication operation.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-scalar-product-metrics">
        <title>Scalar Product, Norm, Distance, and Angle</title>
        <statement>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Scalar Product</title>
                    <p>For two vectors <m>\mathbf{v}</m> and <m>\mathbf{w}</m> in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>, the scalar product is defined as 
                    <me>\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{w} = v_1 w_1 + \dots + v_n w_n</me>.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Norm</title>
                    <p>The norm of a vector <m>\mathbf{v}</m> computes its length and is defined mathematically as 
                    <me>||\mathbf{v}|| = \sqrt{\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{v}} = \sqrt{v_1^2 + \dots + v_n^2}</me>.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Distance</title>
                    <p>The distance between two vectors <m>\mathbf{v}</m> and <m>\mathbf{w}</m> is evaluated as 
                    <me>\operatorname{dist}(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{w}) = ||\mathbf{v}-\mathbf{w}|| = \sqrt{(v_1-w_1)^2 + \dots + (v_n-w_n)^2}</me>.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Angle</title>
                    <p>The angle <m>\varphi</m> between the two vectors <m>\mathbf{v}</m> and <m>\mathbf{w}</m> is given by the formula 
                    <me>\varphi = \arccos\left(\frac{\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{w}}{||\mathbf{v}|| ||\mathbf{w}||}\right)</me>.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Orthogonality</title>
                    <p>Two vectors <m>\mathbf{v}</m> and <m>\mathbf{w}</m> are considered <term>orthogonal</term> if their scalar product evaluates to zero, meaning <m>\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{w} = 0</m>.</p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
        The formula for the norm of a vector might look complex at first glance, but it is simply a direct generalization of the Pythagorean theorem. In two dimensions, a vector <m>\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \end{pmatrix}</m> forms the hypotenuse of a right-angled triangle where the lengths of the legs are given by its components, <m>v_1</m> and <m>v_2</m>. According to Pythagoras, the square of the hypotenuse is <m>v_1^2 + v_2^2</m>, meaning the length itself is <m>\sqrt{v_1^2 + v_2^2}</m>. This exact same geometric logic scales up to three and more dimensions.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-norm-pythagoras">
        <title>Visualizing the Norm via the Pythagorean Theorem</title>
        <image xml:id="img-norm-pythagoras" width="65%">
            <description>A right-angled triangle formed by a vector and its components, with squares drawn on each side to geometrically illustrate that the square of the norm equals the sum of the squares of the components.</description>
            <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                    % Draw grid/axes lightly in background
                    \draw[-&gt;, gray!50] (-4,0) -- (8,0) node[right] {$x$};
                    \draw[-&gt;, gray!50] (0,-4.5) -- (0,8) node[above] {$y$};
                    
                    % 1. Square for the horizontal component (v1)
                    \draw[fill=blue!10, draw=blue, thick] (0,0) -- (4,0) -- (4,-4) -- (0,-4) -- cycle;
                    \node[blue, font=\large] at (2,-2) {Area $= v_1^2$};
                    
                    % 2. Square for the vertical component (v2)
                    \draw[fill=red!10, draw=red, thick] (4,0) -- (4,3) -- (7,3) -- (7,0) -- cycle;
                    \node[red, font=\large] at (5.5,1.5) {Area $= v_2^2$};
                    
                    % 3. Square for the hypotenuse (the vector's norm)
                    \draw[fill=gray!15, draw=black, thick] (0,0) -- (4,3) -- (1,7) -- (-3,4) -- cycle;
                    \node[black, font=\large, align=center] at (0.5,3.5) {Area $= ||\mathbf{v}||^2$ \\ $= v_1^2 + v_2^2$};
                    
                    % Right angle marker
                    \draw[thick] (3.6,0) -- (3.6,0.4) -- (4,0.4);
                    
                    % The legs of the triangle (components)
                    \draw[blue, ultra thick] (0,0) -- (4,0) node[midway, above, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$v_1$};
                    \draw[red, ultra thick] (4,0) -- (4,3) node[midway, left, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$v_2$};
                    
                    % The vector itself (hypotenuse)
                    \draw[-&gt;, black, ultra thick] (0,0) -- (4,3) node[midway, above left, inner sep=2pt] {$||\mathbf{v}|| = \sqrt{v_1^2 + v_2^2}$};
                    
                    % Label the vector endpoint
                    \filldraw[black] (4,3) circle (2pt) node[anchor=south west] {$\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \end{pmatrix}$};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image>
    </figure>

    <example xml:id="ex-scalar-product-norm">
        <title>Lengths and Orthogonality</title>
        <p>
            Consider the vectors <m>\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix}</m> and <m>\mathbf{w} = \begin{pmatrix} -4 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            The norm (length) of <m>\mathbf{v}</m> is:
            <me>||\mathbf{v}|| = \sqrt{3^2 + 4^2} = \sqrt{9 + 16} = \sqrt{25} = 5</me>.
        </p>
        <p>
            The scalar product of <m>\mathbf{v}</m> and <m>\mathbf{w}</m> is:
            <me>\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{w} = (3)(-4) + (4)(3) = -12 + 12 = 0</me>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Because their scalar product is zero, the vectors <m>\mathbf{v}</m> and <m>\mathbf{w}</m> are orthogonal to one another.
        </p>
    </example>

    <exercises xml:id="exercises-vectors-reminder">
        <title>Check Your Understanding</title>

        <exercise xml:id="exer-mc-orthogonal">
            <title>Identifying Orthogonal Vectors</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Which of the following vectors is orthogonal to <m>\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ -3 \end{pmatrix}</m>?</p>
            </statement>
            <choices>
                <choice>
                    <statement><p><m>\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}</m></p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Incorrect. The scalar product is <m>(2)(2) + (-3)(3) = 4 - 9 = -5</m>, not zero.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice correct="yes">
                    <statement><p><m>\begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}</m></p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Correct! The scalar product is <m>(2)(3) + (-3)(2) = 6 - 6 = 0</m>.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice>
                    <statement><p><m>\begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ -3 \end{pmatrix}</m></p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Incorrect. The scalar product is <m>(2)(-2) + (-3)(-3) = -4 + 9 = 5</m>, not zero.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice>
                    <statement><p><m>\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}</m></p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Incorrect. The scalar product is <m>(2)(1) + (-3)(1) = 2 - 3 = -1</m>, not zero.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
            </choices>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="exer-tf-basis">
            <title>Requirements for a Basis</title>
            <statement>
                <p>True or False: Any two non-zero vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> will automatically form a basis for that space.</p>
            </statement>
            <choices>
                <choice>
                    <statement><p>True</p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Incorrect. If the two vectors point in the exact same or opposite direction (for example, <m>\mathbf{v} = (1, 1)</m> and <m>\mathbf{w} = (2, 2)</m>), they are linearly dependent. They do not provide independent geometric directions, so they cannot form a basis.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice correct="yes">
                    <statement><p>False</p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Correct! To form a basis in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>, the two vectors must be linearly independent. If they are collinear (scalar multiples of each other), they fail this requirement.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
            </choices>
        </exercise>

    </exercises>
</subsection>